</div>
<article class="article-content text-gray-700">
<p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-600 mb-8">
                            NexusJudge is an advanced, high-performance online judge designed for competitive programming, educational assessments, and technical interviews. Our platform supports over 20 programming languages and features real-time evaluation with detailed feedback.
                        </p>
<h2>Standard Input and Output</h2>
<p>
                            Most problems on NexusJudge require you to read input from <code>stdin</code> (Standard Input) and write the result to <code>stdout</code> (Standard Output). It is crucial to follow the input/output format specified in the problem statement exactly.
                        </p>
<div class="bg-blue-50 border-l-4 border-blue-500 p-4 mb-6 rounded-r-lg">
<div class="flex">
<span class="material-icons text-blue-500 mr-3">info</span>
<div>
<p class="text-sm text-blue-900 font-medium">Important Note</p>
<p class="text-sm text-blue-800 mt-1">Do not print any extra text like "Enter number:" as it will be considered part of your output and result in a <code>Wrong Answer</code> verdict.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<h3>Example: A + B Problem</h3>
<p>
                            Here is a simple example showing how to read two integers and print their sum in different languages.
                        </p>
<div class="mt-6 mb-8 border border-gray-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
<div class="bg-gray-50 border-b border-gray-200 px-4 py-2 flex gap-4">
<button class="text-sm font-medium text-primary border-b-2 border-primary pb-2 -mb-2.5">C++ 17</button>
<button class="text-sm font-medium text-gray-500 hover:text-gray-700 pb-2">Java</button>
<button class="text-sm font-medium text-gray-500 hover:text-gray-700 pb-2">Python 3</button>
</div>
<div class="bg-gray-50 p-4 overflow-x-auto">
<pre class="!mb-0 !bg-transparent !border-none !p-0"><code class="language-cpp">#include &lt;iostream&gt;
using namespace std;
int main() {
    long long a, b;
    // Fast I/O
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(NULL);
    while (cin &gt;&gt; a &gt;&gt; b) {
        cout &lt;&lt; a + b &lt;&lt; "\n";
    }
    return 0;
}</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<h2>Return Codes</h2>
<p>
                            When your program finishes execution, it must return <code>0</code>. Returning a non-zero value typically indicates a runtime error to the operating system.
                        </p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Accepted (AC):</strong> Your program produced the correct output.</li>
<li><strong>Wrong Answer (WA):</strong> The output differs from the expected answer.</li>
<li><strong>Time Limit Exceeded (TLE):</strong> Your program ran longer than the allowed time limit.</li>
<li><strong>Runtime Error (RE):</strong> Your program crashed (e.g., division by zero, invalid memory access).</li>
</ul>
<h2>Compiler Options</h2>
<p>
                            We use the latest stable compilers. For C++, we use <code>g++</code> with the following flags:
                        </p>
<pre><code>g++ -std=c++17 -O2 -Wall -lm -static -DONLINE_JUDGE source.cpp -o executable</code></pre>
</article>
